Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
set_reinforce_pg_mode(25.10)                      set_reinforce_pg_mode(25.10)

Name
       set_reinforce_pg_mode - Sets global variables for the reinforce_pg com-
       mand

Syntax
        set_reinforce_pg_mode

       [-help]

       [-auto_ir_fix_effort {low | medium | high}]

       [-critical_path_slack {<slack>}]

        [-irdrop_hierarchical_block  {block1 block2 ... | *}]

       [-irdrop_hierarchical_top_rail_analysis_directory {<directory_name>}]

       [-reset]

       [-respect_defined_nets {<file_name>}]

       [-respect_routes {none | fixed | fixed_and_clock | all}]

       [-respect_stdcell_geometry {none | sequential | all}]

       [-timing_aware_effort {none | low | medium | high}]

       Sets global variables for the reinforce_pg command.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each set_reinforce_pg_mode parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and  all  its  parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man set_reinforce_pg_mode

       -auto_ir_fix_effort {low | medium | high}
              Specifies  the  IR fixing effort level during the stripe genera-
              tion. Use this parameter to control the IR  fixing  effort.  The
              number  of  fixed  tiles is changed according to the effort set-
              tings. The higher the effort value, the larger number  of  tiles
              are  passed back from Voltus to RPG for polygon insertion, which
              results in insertion of more polygons.

              This parameter works only with the reinforce_pg -auto_ir_fix pa-
              rameter.

              Default: low

       -critical_path_slack {<slack>}
              Specifies a slack threshold value (in nanoseconds) for  critical
              nets during timing-driven PG stripe reinforcement. It means that
              reinforce_pg  honors  all  the  violation paths with slack value
              lesser than the specified -critical_path_slack value, since  all
              such associated nets are considered critical.

              Default: 0

       -irdrop_hierarchical_block {block1 block2 ... | *}
              Reports  the IR drop violations on the specified list of hierar-
              chical block(s) to fix IR drop. The names of the specified hier-
              archical blocks should be  instantiations  of  the  same  master
              block,  which is the loaded block. If you specify the * value of
              this parameter, all the instantiations of the loaded  block  are
              considered.

       -irdrop_hierarchical_top_rail_analysis_directory {<directory_name>}
              Reads  the  rail  analysis information of full chip available in
              the specified directory for the  hierarchical  flow  blocks.  It
              collects the IR drop information of the specified block and uses
              it to fix the IR drop.

       -reset Resets all or specified parameters to their default values.

       -respect_defined_nets {<file_name>}
              When  this parameter is used, reinforce_pg respects the user-de-
              fined nets listed in the specified file, which are  critical  in
              stripe  generation.  This  helps  in  reserving space around the
              specified nets, and the newly added PG wires are DRC clean  with
              these nets. This parameter is independent of the -respect_routes
              parameter.  However,  when  it  is  used  together with the -re-
              spect_routes parameter, reinforce_pg respects all of them.

              Default: ""

       -respect_routes {none | fixed | fixed_and_clock | all}
              Specifies the route types to honor check of pre-existing  routes
              during stripe generation. This parameter always honor all covers
              and  PGs, but does not honor the trail routes, Following are the
              parameter values:

              * none: Specifies that no route types are respected.

              * fixed: Respects fixed regular wires.

              * fixed_and_clock: Respects fixed and routed clocks.

              * all: Respects fixed and routed clocks along  with  the  routed
                signals.

              For more information on the support of the set_reinforce_pg_mode
              -respect_route  parameter  values  with various statuses of net,
              see Support of  set_reinforce_pg_mode  -respect_route  Parameter
              Values.

              Default: fixed_and_clock

       -respect_stdcell_geometry {none | sequential | all}
              Specifies  all types of geometries (including pin and obs) to be
              respected in via generation. This parameter checks the  standard
              cell  types  to  decide  weather  the  DRC violation needs to be
              checked on its geometries (including pin and obs) in via genera-
              tion.

              Default: all

       -timing_aware_effort {none | low | medium | high}
              Specifies the timing aware effort level on critical paths of re-
              inforce_pg. The reinforce_pg command performs  timing  analysis,
              when  the  -timing_aware_effort parameter is set to low, medium,
              or high. Use the set_reinforce_pg_mode -critical_path_slack  pa-
              rameter to determine the slack range.

              When the set_reinforce_pg_mode -critical_path_slack parameter is
              not  defined,  following will be the behavior of the non-default
              values of -timing_aware_effort:

              * Low Effort: Protects the clock trunk, when this  parameter  is
                set to low.

              * Medium Effort: Protects the clock tree, when this parameter is
                set to medium.

              * High Effort: Protects the clock tree and adds routing blockage
                with  the timing analysis result from first run of polygon in-
                sertion, when this parameter is set to high.

              The -critical_path_slack parameter can work only when the  -tim-
              ing_aware_effort parameter is set to low, medium, or high.

              See  the  figure  below for understanding the timing aware rein-
              force PG flow:

              The following figure presents reserving of spaces around  criti-
              cal  net using with and without the -timing_aware_effort parame-
              ter:

              Default: none

